<br>
as you mentioned, delete is not an option. The guild's name is linked to the MIA guildmaster's account. At BEST, you MIGHT get a different spelling variation, but that will just create confusion and players will keep asking questions...<br>
<br>
For 90 percent of the guild to vote a different leader, u will need about 178 people to vote yes, to have them grant leadership to someone else. Which will be fine with the original owner because if he ever comes back, he can just petition to get leadership back and since the guild is linked to his account, the gm's will just give it back to him. ( I know cuz I have done this already)<br>
<br>
However, since I highly doubt that 178 members are going to do this, you are left with the next step.<br>
<br>
Two of you are still active officers. If you have officer status, that means you have the power to invite. If you are simply lacking members, you can just look for anyone who is the races you accept, and if they dont have a guild tag, ask them to join. Maybe you might have to bypass a few recruitment procedures you are normally used to, but if it saves the guild, then so be it.<br>
<br>
In less than a month, the new expansion will allow all officers and members to call up a list of everyone who is in the guild, whether they are online or not. Maybe if you know these are alts to mains that are no longer in the guild, u can ask them to remove their alts to bring your total roster down or ask them to come back, play their alts more, etc. If you chase enough, maybe you can get your grand total down to a reasonable amount to vote for the new leader??<br>
<br>
Also, what attracts people to guilds are raids. Keep your guild busy. Keep their mind off of the decrease of members and on to getting items and going places. <br>
<br>
Post on your boards that you are aware of the situation and are working to fix it. Communication goes a long way.<br>
<br>
so:<br>
<br>
1) Post on your boards that you are aware of it and fixing it<br>
2) Recruit Recruit Recruit<br>
3) Take new recruits on events/raids<br>
4) Encourage old members to group up and go places with new members<br>
5) Pursue all avenues to contact guildmaster.<br>
6) Group up constantly.<br>
7) Look for raids that other guilds are hosting and get your guys on it in groups. A dragon raid blows away 4 hours or so off of peoples minds and dosent have them thinking how bored they are and how a guild is falling apart, they see it as a guild victory together. <br>
